fields.info: Commuter bus service between Thurston, Pierce and King Counties is popular and demand is growing.  This item adds more service.
fields.name: Add more bus service between counties

fields.info: In vanpools, groups of up to a dozen people share the ride to work.  This takes a lot of cars off the road during rush hours, improving efficiency for everybody.
fields.name: Expand vanpooling

fields.info: Commuter rail could serve people who work near the rail line or can take the bus from the rail station to work.  It runs in the early mornings and late afternoons.
fields.name: Extend commuter rail from Lakewood to Lacey/Centennial Station

fields.info: “Trip reduction” reduces the number of vehicles on the road during rush hour. Working from home and carpooling are examples.  This item expands the region’s successful trip reduction program to most Thurston workers.
fields.name: Get more people to reduce how often they travel alone.

fields.info: Park-and-ride lots are an essential part of the transit system – connecting commuters with buses, vanpools and carpools.
fields.name: Add more park-and-ride lots to support carpooling and riding the bus
Widen I-5 to add a high-occupancy vehicle (HOV) lane in each direction

fields.info: The more connected the local arterial system, the more efficient it is in moving traffic.  This item strategically widens some two lane arterials and makes some key connections.
fields.name: Add lanes to more local roads and link unconnected roads

fields.info: Known as “congestion pricing,” this approach could apply to a single lane, like a HOT lane, or to all lanes.  It’s used during the most crowded periods of the day to encourage people to travel at other times or by other routes.
fields.name: Charge user fees on the freeway, such as in high occupancy toll (HOT) lanes

fields.info: Examples include more electronic message signs, on-ramp signals, cameras, and highway advisory radio. Technology like this provides up-to-the minute traffic information, helps smooth flow, and expedites the response to accidents.
fields.name: Use more technology on the freeway to manage the flow of traffic

fields.info: Adding bike lanes often means widening the road to accommodate the lanes.
fields.name: Add more bike lanes to existing streets

fields.info: Sidewalks and crosswalks encourage us to walk, especially in city and neighborhood centers.  While most new roads have sidewalks and crosswalks, older roads must be retrofitted.
fields.name: Install more sidewalks and crosswalks

fields.info: Local bus service runs along the region’s primary urban corridors.  This item provides more frequent, convenient service along these routes, and extends them to where new shopping and employment centers will develop.
fields.name: Provide more local bus service

fields.info: Dial-a-Lift provides door-to-door bus service for people with limited mobility who travel near the region’s urban corridors.  It is a required part of Intercity Transit’s services.  Because it is customized, it is an expensive service to provide.
fields.name: Maintain para-transit service for people with limited mobility

fields.info: Paved trails, like the Chehalis-Western Trail, enable year-round activity like walking, biking, skating and even bird watching.  They connect communities and attract visitors to our region.
fields.name: Add more major pedestrian and bicycle trails

fields.info: R/T Rural and Tribal Transportation provides  accessible transportation service for south and east Thurston County where no other regular bus service is provided.  It connects with Intercity Transit and other area transit systems.
fields.name: Maintain rural transit service

fields.info: Light rail and trolleys run along urban corridors with high demand for bus service, usually sharing the road with cars, trucks and buses.
fields.name: Build a new light rail or trolley service

fields.info: It’s very costly to replace or retrofit worn or unsafe sections of the roadway system, so regular repair and maintenance make sense.  But existing budgets can’t fully meet the need.
fields.name: Do more pavement repair and roadway maintenance

fields.info: Over the next 20 years, Intercity Transit’s bus fleet will need to be replaced almost 3 times.  The federal government no longer funds this critical investment.
fields.name: Replace buses to keep the fleet in good repair

fields.info:
If we want any new bus or Dial-a-Lift service in the future, the regional bus maintenance an opertions facility will have to be expanded.  It has
reached its limit for the number of vehicles it can service.
fields.name: Expand the transit operations and maintenance center

fields.info: Flooding and fish passage are examples of the environmental challenges to address for existing roadways.  These can be expensive fixes, so they are often addressed either as targeted funding becomes available or as major repair or replacement projects take place.
fields.name: Expedite environmental retrofit projects on existing roadways
